---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'verify';
const description =
  'Bake test, lint, and typecheck commands into context so the agent self-corrects. The single highest-leverage move in this skill.';
---

<Doc
  title={title}
  description={description}
  section="commands"
  sourceFile="skills/groundwork/commands/verify.md"
  templateFiles={[
    'skills/groundwork/templates/hook.sh.template',
    'skills/groundwork/templates/husky-pre-commit.template',
    'skills/groundwork/templates/context-check.yml.template',
  ]}
>
  <p class="doc-lede">
    If the agent does not have verification commands, you become the
    verification step. That is slow and unreliable. <code>verify</code> moves
    the commands to the top of every context file, wires a pre-commit hook,
    and stops the agent from shipping you broken diffs.
  </p>

  <h2>When to use it</h2>
  <p>Every repo, every time. If you only run one command after <code>init</code>, run this one.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Right after <code>init</code> or <code>document</code>.</li>
    <li>Test framework changed.</li>
    <li>New CI pipeline.</li>
    <li><a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> flagged "missing verification".</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Verification section near the top of <code>AGENTS.md</code> (and two-file <code>CLAUDE.md</code>). Fast command in the per-harness pointer files.</li>
    <li><code>.context/hooks/check-context.sh</code>: pre-commit hook for repo-specific drift.</li>
    <li>Hook-runner registration (husky / pre-commit / lefthook) if one is detected. Suggested, not silently installed.</li>
    <li>The detector wired into pre-commit and CI (<code>.github/workflows/context-check.yml</code> if you use Actions).</li>
    <li>A test run of every verification command, so you know the baseline.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Detect.</strong> Reads manifests for <code>test</code>, <code>lint</code>, <code>typecheck</code>, <code>build</code>, <code>format</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Ask.</strong> Detected commands preselected. You adjust. Pick the fast subset (every change) vs the full set (before done).</li>
    <li><strong>Run each command once.</strong> Captures pass / fail. If something is failing, you choose: skip, fix now, or include with a "known failing" note.</li>
    <li><strong>Update the files.</strong> Verification section near the top of each.</li>
    <li><strong>Wire the detector.</strong> <code>npx @ignitic/groundwork detect --fail-on P0</code> in pre-commit and CI.</li>
    <li><strong>Install the local drift hook.</strong> Catches package-manager drift against <code>AGENTS.md</code>, missing ADRs on multi-file commits, ADRs without a Status.</li>
    <li><strong>Register</strong> with your hook runner, or tell you the one-line install.</li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="Fast vs full" tone="mute">
    <p>
      The split matters. If the only option is "run the full suite", agents
      run it once, then never again. Give them a fast loop after every
      change, a full loop before done. Most projects: fast = typecheck +
      lint, full = all four.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <CommandPager slug="verify" />
</Doc>
